@page
@model IndexModel
@{
    ViewData["Title"] = "Home";
}

<section class="hero-panel">
    <span class="eyebrow">Week 7 Project 04</span>
    <h1>Build a complete local Todo API and frontend in one ASP.NET Core app.</h1>
    <p class="lead">
        This project combines a local REST API, an in-memory data store, and a Razor Pages frontend so students can practise
        CRUD operations without any external dependencies.
    </p>
    <div class="action-row">
        <a class="button button-primary" asp-page="/TodoDashboard">Open The Todo Dashboard</a>
        <a class="button button-secondary" href="/api/todoitems" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer">View Raw JSON</a>
    </div>
</section>

<section class="card-grid">
    <article class="info-card">
        <h2>What students practise</h2>
        <ul>
            <li>Create, read, update, and delete todo items through a local API.</li>
            <li>Use correct HTTP status codes for successful and failing requests.</li>
            <li>Handle loading states, clear errors, and success messages.</li>
            <li>Refresh dashboard data automatically with simple polling.</li>
        </ul>
    </article>

    <article class="info-card">
        <h2>Why this app stays local</h2>
        <ul>
            <li>No internet connection is required.</li>
            <li>No database is required because items live in memory.</li>
            <li>No third-party API is required because the backend is part of the same app.</li>
        </ul>
    </article>
</section>

<section class="info-panel">
    <h2>Suggested walkthrough</h2>
    <ol>
        <li>Load the dashboard and inspect the todo list JSON endpoint.</li>
        <li>Create a todo item and confirm the API returns <code>201 Created</code>.</li>
        <li>Update or delete an existing item and observe the summary cards change.</li>
        <li>Wait for the polling refresh and confirm the latest summary time updates automatically.</li>
    </ol>
</section>
